<!--
This file starts empty and grows only from real evidence: user feedback,
failures, reviews, or evals. Never seed it with invented rules.

Promotion criteria:
- 1 occurrence  -> Status: candidate
- 2+ occurrences (same lesson observed again, independently) -> Status: active
- A rule that is outdated, superseded, or conflicts with a newer
  observation -> Status: deprecated (keep it, do not delete, so the
  history of why it changed is preserved)

Every rule MUST be observable and unambiguous — an agent reading it must
be able to check compliance without judgment calls. Do not write rules
using vague words like "appropriately", "properly", "as needed", "when
sensible", "cleanly". Instead state the concrete, checkable action
("Do do X"), name a specific command/pattern/file, or give a checklist.

Initially this file holds everything in one place. If it grows past
roughly 10 active rules or 300 lines, run `scripts/split-learned-rules.sh
--adapter <dir>` to move `Status: active` rule blocks into
`.agent-os/rules/<scope>.md` (global/project/directory/file-pattern, by
each rule's Scope field). This file then keeps an "## Active rules index"
pointing at the moved rules; candidate and deprecated rules always stay
here. After a split, `.agent-os/rules/*.md` is part of this file's active
rules, not a separate concern: agents must read those files too — the
index entries are pointers to binding rule bodies, equally binding as if
they were still listed here.

Rule format (do not deviate):

## Rule: <short name>

Status: candidate | active | deprecated
Source: user-feedback | failure | review | eval
Scope: global | project | directory | file-pattern
Applies to:
- <path or task type>

Rule:
- <observable instruction>

Rationale:
- <why this prevents failure>

Examples:
- Do: <example>
- Do not: <example>

Validation:
- <command or checklist>
-->

